Sometimes it helps to try out Emacs the way someone with more experience has configured it. There are a number of "starter kits" or "distros" that modify Emacs in different ways. Some are lightweight changes to try to provide better defaults. Others modify Emacs extensively. Whether you're starting out or looking around for inspiration, it might be worth trying out a few to see if any of them fit the way you want to work.

Note: The 'starter kits' listed here are those specifically designed for public use (vs. personal configurations posted online).

== Things to know before you start ==

=== Starter kits versus writing your own configuration ===

Starter kits can be a great way to get going quickly. You can try out Emacs with the settings that more experienced users have recommended. If you find something that clicks with your workflow, that can save you a lot of time.

On the other hand, sometimes it's hard to understand all the different changes that a starter kit might make. Growing your configuration slowly, step by step, can help you learn more about how things work.

Many people find it useful to eventually write their own configuration from from scratch, possibly copying the parts they liked from the starter kit they used. If you LearnEmacsLisp, you can make your own Emacs configuration.

It's also okay to continue using a starter kit if you found one that works for you. Some starter kits like DoomEmacs provide a way to integrate your customizations into the starter kit.

=== Basic tutorial ===

If you have not yet read the EmacsTutorial, start with that so that you can understand how to use keyboard shortcuts and commands described in the starter kit documentation. If you prefer a webpage, [https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/tour/ The GNU Emacs Guided Tour] may be useful.

=== Installing and using Git ===

Starter kit installation instructions include steps like "Clone this repository" or "Check out this code." If you come from a non-programming background, you might find it useful to first read a tutorial on how to install and use the Git version control system.

* [https://github.com/git-guides/install-git Git Guides - install git · GitHub]
* [https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Basics-Getting-a-Git-Repository Git - Getting a Git Repository]
* [https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/creating-and-managing-repositories/cloning-a-repository Cloning a repository - GitHub Docs]

=== Using the command line ===

Starter kit installation instructions often assume that you are using Git from the command line so that you can type `git clone ...'. If you are not sure how to open a terminal on your computer,

* *Windows:* Click the start menu, type cmd, and select "Command Prompt". [https://www.dpconline.org/handbook/tool-demos/command-line-intro/command-basics Tutorial]
* *Mac OS X:* Open the Applications folder, open Utilities, and start Terminal. [https://blog.teamtreehouse.com/introduction-to-the-mac-os-x-command-line Tutorial]
* *Linux:* This depends on your distribution of Linux. In general, look for an application that mentions being a terminal or a console. [https://documentation.ubuntu.com/desktop/en/latest/tutorial/the-linux-command-line-for-beginners/ Ubuntu tutorial]

You can use the command-line to try a starter kit without committing to it. If you use `--init-directory' when starting Emacs, you can try many starter kits without committing to using them. For example, if you've checked out [https://codeberg.org/ashton314/emacs-bedrock Emacs Bedrock] into the `emacs-bedrock/' directory, the following command starts an Emacs session with that as the basis.

   emacs --init-directory emacs-bedrock/

=== Finding and editing your init file ===

Starter kits also sometimes ask you to add code to your InitFile (your Emacs configuration file). This file might not exist until you create it. Emacs checks for user configuration in a number of locations, so you might see references to `~/.emacs', `~/.emacs.d/init.el', or `~/.config/emacs/init.el' in people's notes. If you do not know where your init file is located, you can check the variable `user-init-file' with the following command:

   M-x describe-variable RET user-init-file RET

This will show you the current value of `user-init-file' in the part that says "Its value is ...". Take note of that filename (or select and copy it), then open the file. You can open the file by using the menu bar (File - Open File) or by using `M-x find-file'.

After you make any changes suggested by the starter kit, you can save your init file using the menu bar (File - Save) or using `M-x save-buffer'.

To run the code in your current Emacs, you can use `M-x eval-buffer'. Alternatively, you can use `M-x restart-emacs'. You can also start a separate Emacs instead.

=== Literate configurations ===

A number of starter kits use OrgMode to describe the text and embed the code so that they can include more explanations and screenshots. Examples:

* [https://github.com/jamescherti/minimal-emacs.d jamescherti/minimal-emacs.d]
* [https://github.com/MiniApollo/kickstart.emacs kickstart.emacs]
* [https://github.com/MatthewZMD/.emacs.d M-EMACS]
* [https://xgarrido.github.io/emacs-starter-kit/starter-kit.html xgarrido's Emacs Starter Kit]

Because they are written to be read by people as well as by computers, these starter kits might be a good way to learn more about Emacs Lisp along the way.

=== Choosing a starter kit ===

You might want to start by browsing through screenshots or videos about the starter kit to see if it includes the features you are interested in or if it comes with the workflows you are thinking of using.

Here are some questions you can use to help you choose a starter kit:

* What do you want to do with Emacs? A number of starter kits are oriented towards a specific purpose.
** Writing/humanities:
*** [https://github.com/Lambda-Emacs/lambda-emacs Lambda Emacs] Emacs configuration aimed at those engaged in writing and academic work in the humanities
*** [https://github.com/pprevos/emacs-writing-studio Emacs Writing Studio]: focused on writing prose with Org Mode; no-code configuration;
[https://github.com/pprevos/emacs-writing-studio/tree/master/documents has a book], [https://payhip.com/b/alhIJ PDF version is USD 9.99]

* Are you looking for a starter kit that includes specific packages? Take a look at the starter kit description to see if it lists the features it includes.

* Are you looking for specific keyboard shortcut schemes? A starter kit that customizes the keybindings extensively can make it easier for you to get started, although it might be a little harder for you to follow other people's notes if they're writing about functions based on standard Emacs keybindings.
** People who really want to continue using `C-c' to copy and `C-v' to paste might consider [https://github.com/darkstego/wakib-emacs Wakib Emacs]. (On the other hand, it might be worth learning the Emacs shortcuts instead, because `C-c' is very useful as the starting point of other keyboard shortcuts.)
** People who are coming from a Vim background might want to use a starter kit that uses EvilMode to set up Vim-based keybindings, such as DoomEmacs or [[Spacemacs]].

* Do you want something that just changes things slightly or something more extensive?

** Minimalist: just a few changes to Emacs that you can use or read through and adapt to your own configuration
